.TH "nedplayer" "1" "2026-06-09" "NED Player User Manual" ""
.hy
.SH NAME
.PP
nedplayer - runtime player for NED scripting language productions
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\f[B]nedplayer\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
\f[B]nedplayer\f[R] is a runtime engine for productions written in the
NED scripting language, part of the Dead Deer framework developed by
bartoshe.
It is primarily used for demoscene content, interactive presentations
and simple games.
.PP
The player must be invoked from the directory that contains the
\f[B]data/\f[R] sub-directory with a valid \f[B]player.conf\f[R] file.
On startup it reads that configuration file to determine which NED
script to load and which display mode to use.
.PP
The engine supports:
.IP \[bu] 2
OpenGL hardware-accelerated 3-D rendering
.IP \[bu] 2
OpenAL positional audio
.IP \[bu] 2
Vorbis/Ogg music playback
.IP \[bu] 2
JPEG 2000 image decoding
.IP \[bu] 2
TrueType font rendering via FreeType
.IP \[bu] 2
A built-in NED scripting virtual machine for animations, particle
systems, physics and finite-state machines
.SH OPTIONS
.PP
\f[B]nedplayer\f[R] takes no command-line options.
All configuration is read from the \f[B]data/player.conf\f[R] file
located in the current working directory.
.SH FILES
.TP
\f[I]./data/player.conf\f[R]
Main configuration file.
The first line gives the path to the NED script to execute (relative to
the current directory).
Subsequent lines may contain display-mode hints such as
\f[B]fullscreen\f[R], \f[B]windowed\f[R] or \f[B]fullscreenlowres\f[R].
.TP
\f[I]./data/\f[R]
Directory containing all assets (scripts, images, sounds, fonts) used by
the production.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
\f[B]0\f[R]
Normal exit.
.TP
\f[B]non-zero\f[R]
The player could not initialise (missing \f[B]data/player.conf\f[R],
OpenGL context failure, etc.).
.SH BUGS
.PP
No known bugs.
Please report issues to the Debian package maintainer.
.SH SEE ALSO
.PP
The Dead Deer project homepage: <https://deaddeer.free.fr/>
